<p>@DC</p>
<p>That is the problem i have with this transition network thing: they are very good at occupying all the scene in the mediatic arena (one should ask oneself why they get attention in mainstream media..), but they have no clear political visions.</p>
<p>Namely, they have no stated idea on the source of power, money and suggest nothing concrete to break the network of power. The fed banking system and the property system are defended by laws, which are enforced by brute force. And because the law defend the property of polluters and that they have all production tools in their hand, such network cannot have any significant impact if they do not risk confrontation. </p>
<p>At least preppers are honnest with themselves and others: they do not claim they will change the state by miraculous goodwill, they expect the worse to come for sure and advocate to prepare for it. It is may be a more generous attitude than pretending that a transition can take place and leaving people unprepaired.</p>
<p>There is no deep analysis of history in transition networks. Probably they still stick to the legend that a big demonstration of goodwill can impress military, bankers, industrials, civil servant etc&#8230;<br/>
They say we must resist, but how ? with flowers ? with sabotage ?<br/>
In Syria flowers don&#8217;t work, in China either. </p>
<p>I hope something more radical, meaning more profound and honnest in its analysis and more clear on the solution will crystalise among the angry outcasts. May be to be massively preppers is less sexy and pretentious but the way to go. At least there will be no book on that unless it is filled with practical useful solutions.</p>
<p>There is no time for a transition, Action.</p>
